│ THOUGHT                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ I have analyzed the issue and identified the root cause. The SLP vectorizer incorrectly vectorizes `icmp samesign` on `i1` types, leading to `poison` values where a concrete boolean    │
│ should be produced. This is because `i1 0` is considered positive and `i1 1` is considered negative, so their signs are different, and `icmp samesign` on them produces `poison`. The    │
│ original scalar code does not have this issue because the operands are wider integers (`i32`) which have the same sign. The vectorizer truncates the values to `i1` before the           │
│ comparison, which changes the sign semantics.                                                                                                                                            │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ My proposed fix is to disable vectorization of `icmp samesign` instructions when the operand type is `i1`. This is a conservative but safe fix. I will add a check in                    │
│ `SLPVectorizerPass::canVectorizeInstr` for this specific case.                                                                                                                           │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
